>
  <p>Most workplace conflict gets blamed on communication. Someone wasn't clear. Someone didn't listen. Fix the communication, fix the problem.</p>
  <p>Except you've probably watched two clear, reasonable people misunderstand each other completely. So it isn't really about communication. It's about something that happens earlier, and quieter.</p>
  <p>Here's the actual sequence. Someone does something — goes quiet in a meeting, sends a short email, pushes back on a plan. That part is just behavior. Neutral. But nobody experiences behavior neutrally. In the half-second after, we <em>fill in the blank</em>: we assign a reason. <em>He's checked out. She's being territorial. They don't respect the deadline.</em></p>
  <p>And then the move that causes the trouble: we forget we filled in the blank. The interpretation stops feeling like a guess and starts feeling like a fact. We react to the story we wrote, not to what actually happened. By the time it looks like a communication problem, it's been an interpretation problem for a while.</p>
  <p>The quiet one wasn't checked out. He was thinking it through. The territorial one was protecting something she'd worked hard on. The person ignoring the deadline had three other deadlines you didn't know about. None of them were the problem. The <em>story</em> was.</p>
  <p>So here's something you can use immediately. The next time someone on your team does something that lands wrong, before you respond, try one question:</p>

  <h3>What's the most reasonable explanation for what they just did?</h3>
  <p>Not the most generous — generous can feel naive. The most <em>reasonable.</em> Assume they're a competent adult acting on information or pressures you can't see. Then ask them, plainly and without accusation: "Walk me through your thinking on this."</p>
  <p>You'll be right about the hidden reason more often than you'd guess. And even when you're not, you've done something powerful: you've checked the story instead of acting on it. That single habit — checking the interpretation before reacting to it — prevents more conflict than any communication training, because it works on the part that actually breaks.</p>
  <p class="lead">Most personality conflicts aren't personality conflicts. They're two reasonable people reacting to two unchecked stories. Once the stories get checked, the heat goes out of it, and people get back to the work.</p>
